body:
### Summary of the new feature / enhancement

Currently an encoding instance can't be converted from a `string` (or `int`) using a PowerShell syntax like:

```powershell
[System.Text.Encoding]'utf8'
```

Some encodings can only be created using the a static accessor, e.g.:

```powershell
[System.Text.Encoding]::ascii
```

Some encoding names (as `bigendianutf32`) are PowerShell specific and can only be created using the static `GetEncoding()` method, e.g.:

```powershell
[System.Text.Encoding]::GetEncoding('utf-32BE')
```

Some PowerShell encoding definitions are dynamic and e.g. depend on the operating system (as e.g.: `oem`)

Somehow these specific issues appeared to be worked around and [patched in version `6.2`](https://learn.microsoft.com/powershell/module/microsoft.powershell.utility/out-file?view=powershell-7.6#-encoding):
<sup>(I have no clue how this works considering that the parameter type is still `System.Text.Encoding`)</sup>

> Beginning with PowerShell 6.2, the Encoding parameter also allows numeric IDs of registered code pages (like -Encoding 1251) or string names of registered code pages (like -Encoding "windows-1251"). For more information, see the .NET documentation for [Encoding.CodePage](https://learn.microsoft.com/en-us/dotnet/api/system.text.encoding.codepage?view=netcore-2.2).

But that can't be used for custom functions:

```powershell
function myFunction {
    param (
        [System.Text.Encoding]$Encoding
    )
    Write-Warning $Encoding
}

myFunction utf8
```

```PowerShell
myFunction: Cannot process argument transformation on parameter 'Encoding'. Cannot convert the "utf8" value of type "System.String" to type "System.Text.Encoding".
```

Which also reveals from mocking existing cmdlets that support the `-Enconding` parameter (see: [Pester#1877](https://github.com/pester/Pester/issues/1877#issuecomment-4851470064)):

```powershell
BeforeAll {
    function InvokeOutFile {
        Write-Output "Hello World" | Out-File -Encoding utf8 -FilePath pathToFile
    }
}

Describe "Out-File encoding" {

    Context "Mocking" {
        It "InvokeOutFile" {
            Mock Out-File { 'Mocked' }
            InvokeOutFile | Should -Be Mocked
        }
    }
}
```

